{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17590601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17590601"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:49:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:49:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15207"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15207"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.04,0.24,0.4,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7898"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66593"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7898"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15207"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52046"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"461"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1144"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19248"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21317"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66593"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents with a three-month history of difficulty swallowing that has become progressively worse. He has been regurgitating some of his solid meals. He reports weight loss of 10 kg over this period. In the last two weeks he has noticed some hoarseness. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and drinks about four glasses of wine a day. His history includes gastro-oesophageal reflux disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBearing in mind the likely diagnosis, the significance of his various symptoms must be considered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following symptoms is of most concern?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The progressive dysphagia","The regurgitation","The hoarseness","The weight loss","The history of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAlmost certainly this patient has a carcinoma of the oesophagus. He has three risk factors, namely, his tobacco and alcohol use and the history of \u003Cstrong\u003Egastro-oesophageal reflux disease\u003C/strong\u003E. Oesophageal squamous cell carcinoma typically presents with \u003Cstrong\u003Eprogressive dysphagia \u003C/strong\u003Ethat is worse for solids than liquids. This occurs due to gradual narrowing of the oesophageal lumen by the growing tumour. Likewise, the narrowing of the lumen might also lead to \u003Cstrong\u003Eregurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E of food. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eweight loss\u003C/strong\u003E would be related to the patient\u0027s reduced food intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most worrying feature is the \u003Cstrong\u003Ehoarseness. \u003C/strong\u003EWhilst this could be related to his smoking, the concern is whether this is due to recurrent laryngeal nerve involvement\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Efrom direct extension of the tumour. If the hoarseness was related to his smoking, it is most likely that this symptom would have been present for a long time - probably many years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf this patient does have extension of tumour into his recurrent laryngeal nerve, any treatment is likely to be palliative.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Carcinoma of the oesophagus typically presents with progressive dysphagia, worse for solids than liquids","Oesophageal cancer can invade local structures causing hoarseness through recurrent laryngeal nerve involvement"],"references":["Wang Y, Mukkamalla SKR, Singh R, Babiker HM, Lyons S. Esophageal Cancer. 2024 Aug 17. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29083661","Codipilly DC, Wang KK. Squamous Cell Carcinoma of the Esophagus. Gastroenterol Clin North Am. 2022 Sep;51(3):457-484. doi: 10.1016/j.gtc.2022.06.005. Epub 2022 Aug 29. PMID: 36153105","Hadian Y, Howell JY, Ramsey ML, et al. Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma. [Updated 2024 Jul 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441939/","Que SKT, Zwald FO, Schmults CD. Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma: Incidence, risk factors, diagnosis, and staging. J Am Acad Dermatol. 2018 Feb;78(2):237-247. doi: 10.1016/j.jaad.2017.08.059. PMID: 29332704"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52046"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15207"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52046"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T13:03:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T13:05:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7898"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66593"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"met